## Bead Creation (post-approval)

When crew approves the plan, create child beads:

```bash
PARENT="<bead-id>"

# Phase 1 — example
SETUP=$(bd create "Set up Supabase project" \
  --parent $PARENT -t task \
  --label needs-human \
  -d "Provision Supabase project, capture connection strings, add to env config. MANUAL STEP — human required." \
  --json | jq -r '.id')

MIGRATIONS=$(bd create "Create database schema migrations" \
  --parent $PARENT -t task \
  -d "Implement migrations per architecture doc." \
  --json | jq -r '.id')

# Wire dependencies — CRITICAL: syntax is `bd dep add CHILD PARENT`
# Read as: "CHILD needs PARENT to be done first"
# WRONG: bd dep add $SETUP $MIGRATIONS  (would mean setup needs migrations — backwards)
# RIGHT: bd dep add $MIGRATIONS $SETUP  (migrations needs setup — correct)
bd dep add $MIGRATIONS $SETUP

# Label automated tasks for polecat pool
bd list --parent $PARENT --status open --json | \
  jq -r '.[] | select(.labels | map(.name) | contains(["needs-human"]) | not) | .id' | \
  xargs -I {} bd update {} --label pool:{{.Rig}}/polecat
```

**Dependency direction rule**: `bd dep add CHILD PARENT` — think "CHILD *needs* PARENT", not "PARENT *comes before* CHILD". Temporal language ("A before B", "Phase 1 then Phase 2") inverts the argument order. Always verify: `bd blocked <child-id>` should show the parent as a blocker.

After creating all beads, mail crew + nudge with a summary of what was created.

